e in the garden, and I was afraid, because I was naked; and I hid myself.''</ref>\n\n[Repeat verses 1 & 2]\n\nYou know Christ had twelve apostles<ref>Luke 6:13 ''And when it was day, he called unto him his disciples: and of them he chose twelve, whom also he named apostles.''</ref>\nAnd three he led away<ref>Matthew 26:36-38 ''Then cometh Jesus with them unto a place called Gethsemane, and saith unto the disciples, Sit ye here, while I go and pray yonder. And he took with him Peter and the two sons of Zebedee, and began to be sorrowful and very heavy. Then saith he unto them, My soul is exceeding sorrowful, even unto death: tarry ye here, and watch with me.''</ref>\nHe said, \"Watch with me one hour,<ref>Matthew 26:40 ''And he cometh unto the disciples, and findeth them asleep, and saith unto Peter, What, could ye not watch with me one hour?''</ref>\n'till I go yonder and pray.\"\n\n[Repeat verses 1 & 2]\n\nChrist came on Easter morning\nMary and Martha went down to see<ref>Matthew 28:1 ''In the end of the sabbath, as it began to dawn toward the first day of the week, came Mary Magdalene and the other Mary to see the sepulchre.''</ref>\nHe said, \"Go tell my disciples<ref>Matthew 28:5-7 ''And the angel answered and said unto the women, Fear not ye: for I know that ye seek Jesus, which was crucified. He is not here: for he is risen, as he said. Come, see the place where the Lord lay. And go quickly, and tell his disciples that he is risen from the dead; and, behold, he goeth before you into Galilee; there shall ye see him: lo, I have told you.''</ref>\nTo meet me in Galilee.\"<ref>Matthew 26:32 ''But after I am risen again, I will go before you into Galilee.''  A variety of spiritual meanings have been attached to this line (see, for example, {{cite web|url=http://www.springwater-pres.org/sermon-Easter-05.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-09-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725040922/http://www.springwater-pres.org/sermon-Easter-05.html |archivedate=2008-07-25 }}).</ref>\n\n[Repeat verses 1 & 2]}}\n\nThis version was included on the 1965 album ''The Legendary Son House: Father of the Folk Blues'' (Columbia).  An alternate version from the same session is found on the 1992 reissue ''Son House \u2014 Father of the Delta Blues: The Complete 1965 Sessions'' (Columbia).\n\n==Depeche Mode Version==\nEnglish [[electronic music]] band [[Depeche Mode]] recorded a response to \"John the Revelator\" in 2005. It was released on ''[[Playing the Angel]]'' and the ''[[John the Revelator / Lilian]]'' single. Songwriter [[Martin Gore]] described the song as \"a heavily re-interpreted old gospel tune about the author of the Book of Revelation\". The band rejects the original's unwavering faith with the response \"Armageddon? Gee, thanks.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Fortner |first=Stephen |date=November 1, 2005 |title=Depeche Mode -- The Grand Architects of Electronic Pop Play It Analog on Playing The Angel |magazine=Keyboard |publisher=NewBay Media LLC}}</ref>\n\n==References and notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Blind Willie Johnson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John The Revelator (Song)}}\n[[Category:Year of song unknown]]\n[[Category:Songwriter unknown]]\n[[Category:Blind Willie Johnson songs]]\n[[Category:Gospel songs]]\n[[Category:Blues songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of religious leaders]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n[[Category:Music based on the Bible]]\n", "name_user": "Coryphantha", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add Curtis Stigers version of this song from the show Sons of Anarchy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_the_Revelator_(song)"}
